---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { GA_MEASUREMENT_ID } from '../config/analytics';

const analyticsAvailable = Boolean(GA_MEASUREMENT_ID);
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy"
  description="How peterghiorse.com handles analytics, newsletter subscriptions, cookies, and personal information."
>
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16 md:py-24">
    <p class="mb-4 text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-(--color-primary)">Privacy</p>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold text-(--color-text)">A small site with a small data footprint.</h1>
    <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-(--color-text-muted)">
      I use data to learn whether the writing reaches people—not to build advertising profiles. This page explains what the site can collect and the choices you control.
    </p>

    <div class="prose mt-12">
      <h2>Website analytics</h2>
      <p>
        If you choose “Allow analytics,” this site loads Google Analytics 4. It can record page views, the channel or campaign that referred a visit, landing pages, reading signals, newsletter and related-post activity, external-link clicks, share actions, and contact-link clicks.
      </p>
      <p>
        Analytics is off until you opt in. Advertising storage, ad personalization, and Google Signals are disabled. I do not send your name, email address, article form input, or other directly identifying information to Google Analytics. Google may still process device, browser, approximate-location, and network information under its own terms. Read <a href="https://policies.google.com/privacy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Google's privacy policy</a> for details.
      </p>

      <h2>Referral measurement and identity</h2>
      <p>
        Links from LinkedIn, Substack, GitHub, newsletters, or outreach may include standard campaign parameters. The site keeps an allow-listed source, medium, campaign, link placement, landing path, and referring hostname in session storage so the original referral is not lost as you move between pages. It never stores the full referring URL or its query string.
      </p>
      <p>
        When analytics loads, the page location sent to Google is rebuilt with only those aggregate campaign parameters, and the referrer is reduced to its hostname. Unrecognized query parameters and full referrer paths are removed before the analytics configuration is sent.
      </p>
      <p>
        These signals identify a channel or campaign, not a person. If you choose an email link, the site can add that aggregate referral context to the visible draft so I can connect the source to your message after you intentionally identify yourself by sending it. You can edit or remove that text before sending. Names, email addresses, companies, and person-specific codes are not sent to Google Analytics.
      </p>

      <h2>Newsletter subscriptions</h2>
      <p>
        Newsletter signup is provided by <a href="https://peterghiorse.substack.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Substack</a>. When you enter an email address in its embedded form, that information goes directly to Substack; it does not pass through this site's analytics. Substack controls its signup form, subscriber records, emails, and associated cookies under <a href="https://substack.com/privacy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Substack's privacy policy</a>.
      </p>

      <h2>Browser storage</h2>
      <p>
        The site stores two lasting preferences in your browser: your light/dark theme and your analytics choice. It also keeps the allow-listed referral context above in session storage, which normally disappears when the browser tab or session ends. If you allow analytics, Google Analytics may also set cookies beginning with <code>_ga</code>. Choosing “Disable analytics” below stops further analytics events from this site and removes accessible <code>_ga</code> cookies for this domain.
      </p>

      <h2>Your choice</h2>
      {analyticsAvailable ? (
        <div class="not-prose flex flex-wrap gap-3">
          <button
            type="button"
            data-analytics-consent="accepted"
            class="rounded-xl bg-(--color-primary) px-4 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-white hover:bg-(--color-primary-dark)"
          >Enable analytics</button>
          <button
            type="button"
            data-analytics-consent="declined"
            class="rounded-xl border border-(--color-border) px-4 py-2 text-sm font-semibold text-(--color-text) hover:bg-(--color-surface-alt)"
          >Disable analytics</button>
        </div>
      ) : (
        <p>Analytics is not configured on this deployment, so no analytics script is loaded.</p>
      )}

      <h2>Questions</h2>
      <p>
        If you have a privacy question, use the <a href="/contact">contact page</a>. This notice was last updated July 22, 2026.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
